# Security Architecture Spec

## Scope

Defense-in-depth, authorization, step-up authentication, session trust, adaptive
load shedding, auditability, tenant isolation, and the mandatory policy boundary
for security-sensitive backend work.

## Load when

Changing authentication, authorization, roles, permissions, users, sessions,
passwords, TOTP, API keys, rate limiting, cached shells, audit events, tenant
boundaries, Turnstile, security metrics, or any privileged/sensitive action.

## Owns

- Policy target: `backend/internal/security/` (`PagePolicy` is implemented; broader
  user/session policy centralization remains planned)
- Current auth/session code: `backend/internal/auth/`, `backend/internal/session/`
- Current RBAC code: `backend/internal/user/`, `backend/internal/middleware/perm.go`
- Rate limiting: `backend/middleware/ratelimit.go`, `backend/ratelimit/`
- Audit/event storage: `backend/internal/events/`, `backend/models/analytics.go`
- Tenant boundary: `grengo/`, generated tenant env, database, Redis, and uploads
- Implementation plan: `.todo/security_invariants_hardening`

## Threat Model

Skaia assumes any one control can fail. Security must remain intact when an
attacker bypasses or exhausts one layer, and when generated code omits a local
check. Controls therefore compose independently and fail closed:

`rate limit => cached shell => session risk => Turnstile => TOTP => power/RBAC
=> superuser isolation => audit => tenant isolation`

AI-generated code is an explicit threat source. A handler-local permission check
is not an architectural invariant and must not be treated as one.

## Required Invariants

### Privilege and authorization

- User-management authorization requires `actorPower > targetPower`; equality is
  denied. No ordinary bypass may manage equal or higher power.
- Superusers may bypass ordinary permission membership, but may not directly
  manage another superuser. Superuser demotion uses the dedicated collective
  demotion flow.
- Assigning or creating a role may never grant power at or above the actor's
  power, or permissions the actor is not authorized to delegate.
- Every privileged service operation must call one centralized, fail-closed
  policy API. Frontend checks, route grouping, and scattered handler checks are
  defense-in-depth only.
- Required policy concepts are `CanManageUser`, `RequirePowerLevel`, and
  `RequirePermission`. They return typed decisions/errors and never write HTTP
  responses or silently discard lookup failures.
- Permission storage and middleware must share one documented superuser rule;
  conflicting middleware/service interpretations are forbidden.
- Interactive page response moderation/deletion uses `security.PagePolicy` through
  a required page-service dependency; owner, editor, and `home.manage` decisions
  fail closed on missing dependencies or lookup errors.
- Section-preset create/update/delete calls a required service-level
  `home.manage` policy. JWT route grouping and handler checks are not the
  authorization boundary, and permission-store failures deny mutation.

### Step-up and session trust

- Sensitive actions require a fresh, action-bound, session-bound, single-use,
  short-lived step-up grant. Authentication at login is not sufficient.
- Sensitive actions include role/permission changes, password resets, TOTP
  disablement, API-key creation, session revocation, recovery resolution, and
  every superuser action. New actions of equivalent impact join this set by
  default.
- `RequireTOTP` and `RequireTrustedSession` are centralized policy gates. The
  grant identifies actor, session, action, target/resource, issued time, expiry,
  and consumption state; changing any binding requires a new challenge.
- TOTP verification is unconditional once requested. Codes must use an explicit
  validation window owned by Skaia; library defaults are not policy. Replay in
  the accepted time step must be prevented for sensitive-action grants.
- Expired, consumed, mismatched, or missing grants fail closed. Expiration never
  auto-issues another challenge; the client explicitly requests a new one.
- Challenge responses carry a stable reason code and optional server-owned action
  label. Clients show the exact trigger and never infer it from the current URL.
- Trust belongs to a server-side session, never to an IP, browser, user account,
  or all tabs globally. One trusted session cannot elevate another.
- Sessions record `created_ip`, `last_seen_ip`, and a user-agent hash. IP or user
  agent changes raise risk and trigger step-up rather than immediate account
  denial. A session remains restricted until verification succeeds.
- Turnstile may precede TOTP for anomalous sessions but never replaces TOTP for a
  sensitive action that requires it.
- Access JWTs remain short lived and session state remains revocable server side.

### Availability and containment

- DEFCON budgets measure weighted work, not only request count. Expensive routes
  consume more budget; pressure and jailed populations reduce available budget.
- Rejection happens in Redis/middleware before database, SSR, or expensive Go
  work whenever possible. Limiter failure behavior must be explicit and tested.
- Under pressure, public reads may serve a generic cached shell instead of DB,
  SSR, SEO, or other tenant computations. Cached shells contain no user/session
  data and never satisfy authenticated mutations.
- Trust/bypass is user-session scoped. Clearing an IP jail must not release other
  users sharing that NAT.
- Tenant data is isolated by database, Redis namespace, upload root, runtime env,
  and host routing. Cross-tenant identifiers and cache keys are never accepted
  without resolving the current tenant boundary.
- Normalized custom-page contracts resolve only embedded schemas. User config
  cannot trigger remote schema fetches; CSS colors require explicit safe-value
  validation, and contract errors never echo page config or response values.
  Typed config decoding is size/depth bounded and rejects duplicate JSON keys.
- Custom-page shadow telemetry contains hashes, counts, field names, and bounded
  reason codes only. It never stores page content, config values, answers,
  respondent data, or idempotency keys. Phase 4 projectors strip interactive
  records/result summaries. Response migration telemetry likewise contains only
  parity hashes, counts, and mismatch codes; answers, respondents, record IDs,
  raw idempotency keys, and idempotency hashes never enter logs or API payloads.
  Normalized-response readiness or storage failures strip runtime projections
  and deny mutations instead of falling back to potentially stale sensitive data.
  After normalized read cutover, definition/response projection or readiness
  failures fail the read rather than consulting `pages.content`; authorization
  filtering remains identical across storage modes. Cutover telemetry is also
  content-free, and external-job absence requires explicit operator review
  because application request telemetry cannot prove it.
- Palette references use page-scoped foreign keys; deleting a referenced token
  fails closed. A token reference that has no declared page token is quarantined
  rather than becoming an unconstrained CSS variable reference.
- Typed page definition and palette writes call the centralized
  `PagePolicy.RequirePageEditor` service gate. Missing policy, page/editor lookup
  failure, permission lookup failure, an unmatched shadow, missing expected
  revision, or stale revision all deny before mutation. Conflict and validation
  responses contain no section config or interactive runtime data.

### Audit and observability

- Security audit records are append-only through application APIs. They cover
  login outcomes, TOTP failures, challenge issue/expiry/consumption, role and
  permission changes, superuser actions, IP/user-agent changes, permission
  denials, API-key actions, and session revocations.
- Records include tenant, actor, target/resource, session, action, outcome,
  reason code, request correlation ID, source IP metadata, and timestamp. They do
  not contain passwords, TOTP/API secrets, raw tokens, or sensitive payloads.
- Security events and limiter telemetry use structured logs and bounded metrics.
  Required views include DEFCON state, jailed users, weighted request cost,
  authentication events, superuser activity, and per-tenant activity.
- Audit write failure policy is explicit per action. High-impact mutations fail
  closed or use a durable transactional/outbox mechanism; silent loss is forbidden.

## Current Baseline (2026-06-19)

- Strict power comparison exists for several user/role handlers, but it is
  fragmented and `CheckManagePowerLevel` writes HTTP from the user service.
- `PermissionMiddleware` grants admin/superuser bypass from JWT claims, while
  repository `HasPermission` checks permission membership only. The rule is not
  centralized.
- MFA challenge expiry and recovery action binding exist in selected flows, but
  fresh step-up is not enforced for every sensitive action.
- `totp.Validate` currently uses the dependency's default skew of one adjacent
  period; exact-cycle validation is not implemented as a Skaia invariant.
- Stateful `sessions` track IP and user-agent hash and can use Turnstile on an IP
  change. Trust is a boolean and is not yet a general action/session grant model.
- DEFCON weighted limiting and priority bypass primitives exist. Generic cached
  pressure shells, comprehensive audit coverage, anomaly detection, and unified
  security metrics remain incomplete.
- Database, Redis-prefix, upload-directory, env-file, and host-routing tenant
  boundaries exist; verification must accompany every new storage path.

## Change Rules

- Do not add a sensitive route until its service-level policy gate, audit event,
  denial behavior, and focused tests exist.
- Do not copy authorization or step-up logic into a domain. Extend the central
  policy package and use it from the service operation.
- Never treat claims, client state, IP allowlists, or successful Turnstile as
  proof of fresh TOTP or trusted-session authorization.
- Security lookup, cache, challenge-store, and audit failures must never become
  authorization success through ignored errors.
- Any intentional exception requires a spec change, threat analysis, tests, and
  auditor review in the same work item.

## Verify

- Centralization drift: `rg "CheckManagePowerLevel|HasPermission|PermissionMiddleware|VerifyTOTP" backend/internal backend/middleware -n`
- Session schema/logic: `backend/internal/migrations/012_sessions.sql`,
  `backend/internal/session/*_test.go`
- Auth challenge logic: `backend/internal/auth/service.go`,
  `backend/internal/middleware/mfarequired.go`
- Full backend check:
  `env GOCACHE=/tmp/skaia-go-cache GOTMPDIR=/tmp JWT_SECRET=test-secret go test ./...`
- Security-sensitive changes require focused denial, equality, expiry, replay,
  cross-session, cross-tenant, audit-failure, and dependency-failure tests.

